Now I have a thorough picture of all the files. Let me compile the findings.

---

## Code Efficiency Review

Reviewing: `server/middleware/rateLimiter.js`, `server/server.js`, `client/src/components/SidebarOpinions/` (5 files), `client/src/components/mentions/useMentionAutocomplete.js`, `client/src/components/Notifications/` (2 files).

---

## Critical Issues

### 1. Icon Lookup via `.map()` Renders Empty DOM Nodes for Every Notification - Confidence: 97

**Files:**
- `client/src/components/Notifications/UnreadNotificationCard.jsx` lines 212-216
- `client/src/components/Notifications/notificationsCards.jsx` lines 258-263

Both notification components iterate the entire icon array for every notification card and render a `<div className="notification-icon">` wrapper for every entry regardless of whether it matches, outputting `null` children for non-matching types. With 7-9 icons in the array and a page of 5-50 notifications, this produces up to 450 empty DOM nodes per render and forces React to reconcile all of them.

`UnreadNotificationCard.jsx` (no `useMemo`, no guard — the entire array loops on every render):
```jsx
// Lines 212-216 — renders 7 <div> wrappers per notification, 6 with null children
{iconArray.map((icon, index) => (
    <div className="notification-icon" key={index}>
        {icon.type === displayType ? icon.icon : null}
    </div>
))}
```

`notificationsCards.jsx` has the same pattern inside the `else` branch (lines 258-263).

**Fix — build a `Map` at module level and look up in O(1), rendering exactly one element:**

```js
// Module-level — computed once
const ICON_MAP = new Map(NOTIFICATION_ICON_ARRAY.map(entry => [entry.type, entry.icon]));

// Inside render:
<div className="notification-icon">
    {ICON_MAP.get(displayType) ?? null}
</div>
```

This eliminates the loop entirely and removes all empty wrapper `<div>` nodes.

---

### 2. Metrics Middleware Monkey-Patches `res.write` and `res.end` on Every Request - Confidence: 92

**File:** `server/server.js` lines 550-616

The middleware unconditionally wraps `res.write` and `res.end` with closure-capturing functions on **every** incoming request, including `/health`, static redirects, and 404s. Each wrap allocates a new closure, a `byteCount` variable, and re-binds the response methods. On a high-traffic server this adds measurable GC pressure and function-call overhead on the critical hot path.

```js
// Lines 557-576 — runs on EVERY request, always
const originalWrite = res.write.bind(res);
const originalEnd = res.end.bind(res);

res.write = (chunk, encoding, callback) => { ... };
res.end   = (chunk, encoding, callback) => { ... };
```

The health check endpoint at `/health` is an especially clear victim: it does no meaningful work yet still pays the full monkey-patch cost.

**Fix — gate on a flag, or skip known cheap routes:**

```js
app.use((req, res, next) => {
    metricsState.requests += 1;
    metricsState.inFlight += 1;

    // Skip byte-counting overhead for health/metrics endpoints
    const skipByteCount = req.path === '/health' || req.path === '/api/health'
        || req.path === '/metrics' || req.path === '/api/metrics';

    const startNs = process.hrtime.bigint();
    let byteCount = 0;

    if (!skipByteCount) {
        const originalWrite = res.write.bind(res);
        const originalEnd = res.end.bind(res);
        res.write = (chunk, encoding, callback) => { ... };
        res.end   = (chunk, encoding, callback) => { ... };
    }
    // ... res.on('finish') still fires for counting/timing
    next();
});
```

A more thorough improvement would be to opt-in via a flag (e.g. only patch for `/api/` prefixed routes) rather than opt-out.

---

### 3. `abortRef` Is Declared but Never Used — In-Flight Fetches Are Never Cancelled - Confidence: 95

**File:** `client/src/components/mentions/useMentionAutocomplete.js` lines 13, 32-50

`abortRef` is declared at line 13 but never assigned or used. When a user types quickly (e.g. `@jo`, `@joh`, `@john`), the debounce correctly cancels pending *timers*, but any fetch that **already started** before the next keystroke fires is not aborted. All three requests will resolve and call `setResults`, causing stale earlier queries to overwrite more-recent ones.

```js
const abortRef = useRef(null);  // line 13 — declared, never written

debounceRef.current = setTimeout(async () => {
    try {
        // abortRef.current is never passed here — no cancellation
        const res = await searchUsers(q, 6);
        ...
    }
}, DEBOUNCE_MS);
```

**Fix — abort the previous controller when a new fetch starts:**

```js
debounceRef.current = setTimeout(async () => {
    // Cancel any previous in-flight fetch
    if (abortRef.current) abortRef.current.abort();
    abortRef.current = new AbortController();
    const signal = abortRef.current.signal;

    try {
        const res = await searchUsers(q, 6, signal); // pass signal through to fetch
        if (signal.aborted) return;
        ...
    } catch (err) {
        if (err?.name === 'AbortError') return; // expected, not an error
        ...
    }
}, DEBOUNCE_MS);
