### 6. Profile Share Image: `overlayBuffer` and Avatar Processing Are Sequential When They Could Be Parallel - Confidence: 83

**File:** `server/server.js` lines 711-737

After `baseLayer` is produced, the dark overlay SVG conversion (line 714) and the avatar fetch + resize + circular-clip (lines 724-737) are performed sequentially. These two operations are fully independent — the overlay does not depend on the avatar and vice versa. Both involve CPU-bound Sharp processing, and the avatar additionally has a network fetch.

```js
// line 714 — overlay computed
const overlayBuffer = await sharp(Buffer.from(overlaySvg)).png().toBuffer();

// line 724-737 — avatar fetched and processed AFTER overlay, but has no dependency on it
const remote = await fetchRemoteImageBuffer(avatarEval.resolvedUrl);
const resizedAvatar = await sharp(remote.buffer, ...).resize(...).png().toBuffer();
const circularAvatar = await sharp(resizedAvatar).composite([...]).png().toBuffer();
```

**Fix — run overlay conversion and avatar fetch/process in parallel:**
```js
const [overlayBuffer, avatarComposite] = await Promise.all([
    sharp(Buffer.from(overlaySvg)).png().toBuffer(),
    avatarUrl
        ? (async () => {
            const avatarEval = evaluateShareImageCandidate(avatarUrl);
            if (!avatarEval.ok) return null;
            try {
                const remote = await fetchRemoteImageBuffer(avatarEval.resolvedUrl);
                const circleMask = Buffer.from(`<svg ...>`);
                const resized = await sharp(remote.buffer, ...).resize(avatarSize, avatarSize, { fit: 'cover' }).png().toBuffer();
                return await sharp(resized).composite([{ input: circleMask, blend: 'dest-in' }]).png().toBuffer();
            } catch { return null; }
        })()
        : Promise.resolve(null)
]);
```

This can shave several hundred milliseconds off uncached profile share image generation, since the avatar network fetch (7s timeout budget) otherwise blocks the trivially fast SVG render.

